```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <map>
#include <set>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ifstream fin("datorii.in");
    ofstream fout("datorii.out");

    int C, D;
    fin >> C >> D;

    unordered_map<string, pair<long long, long long>> firms;
    set<string> distinct_firms;

    for (int i = 0; i < D; ++i) {
        string firmX, firmY, temp;
        long long amount;
        fin >> firmX >> temp >> firmY >> amount;

        firms[firmX].first += amount; // firmX owes amount
        firms[firmY].second += amount; // firmY is owed amount

        distinct_firms.insert(firmX);
        distinct_firms.insert(firmY);
    }

    if (C == 1) {
        fout << distinct_firms.size() << endl;
    } else if (C == 2) {
        map<string, pair<long long, long long>> sorted_firms(firms.begin(), firms.end());

        for (const auto& entry : sorted_firms) {
            fout << entry.first << " " << entry.second.first << " " << entry.second.second << endl;
        }
    }

    fin.close();
    fout.close();

    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of the code:
1. We include necessary headers for file operations and data structures.
2. We declare `main()` where we read from the input file `datorii.in` and write to the output file `datorii.out`.
3. We read the input values: `C` (the requirement to be solved) and `D` (the number of debt records).
4. We use an unordered_map `firms` to store each firm's debt (`first` of the pair) and the amount owed to them (`second` of the pair) and a set `distinct_firms` to keep track of all distinct firms.
5. We loop through the debt records, updating the `firms` map and `distinct_firms` set accordingly.
6. Depending on the value of `C`, we either print the number of distinct firms (if `C == 1`) or print each firm's name followed by the sum of debts and sums owed to them in lexicographical order (if `C == 2`).
7. Finally, we close the input and output files.

This solution ensures efficient reading and writing operations and handles the constraints effectively.
